data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration is needed here.**

Your code only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — none of which are affected by the .NET Framework → .NET 8 migration. These APIs work identically in modern .NET. There are no references to `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`, or `Thread.Interrupt`.

This code will compile and run correctly as-is on .NET 8.

---

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort):

You could simplify this with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run`, but that's a separate concern:

```csharp
public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    Parallel.ForEach(items, item =>
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

⚠️ Also note the classic closure-over-loop-variable bug in your original code — `item` is captured by reference. In C# 5+ (which .NET 8 uses), `foreach` variables are scoped per iteration, so this is actually safe. But if this were a `for` loop with an index, you'd need a local copy.
